Problem 7.3

rr data(2013, package = ) VoteResults <- Minneapolis2013 %>% group_by(Second) %>% summarise( votes = n() ) VoteResults r VoteResults %>% ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Second, desc(votes)), y = votes )) + geom_bar(stat = ‘identity’) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1)) + ylab() + xlab()

  1. How many cases are there?
  • There are 80101 cases in Minneapolis2013 data.

rr VoteResults %>% arrange( desc(votes) ) %>% head()

  1. Who were the top 5 candidates in the Second vote selections.
  • Betsy Hodges, Don Samuels, Mark Andrew, Jackie Cheeryhomes,and Bob Fine.
  1. How many ballots are marked “undervote” in
  • First choice selections?
    • 1 undervote
  • Second choice selections?
    • 1 undervote
  • Third choice selections?
    • 1 undervote

rr Minneapolis2013 %>% group_by(Third) %>% summarise(count = n())

  1. What are the top 3 combinations of First and Second vote selections? (That is, of all the possible ways a voter might have marked his or her first and second choices, which received the highest number of votes?)
  • The top 3 combinations of First and Second vote selections are: 1. Betsy Hodges and Mark Andrew, 2.Betsy Hodges and Don Samuels, 3. Mark Andrew and Betsy Hodges.

rr Combination <- Minneapolis2013 %>% group_by(First, Second) %>% summarise( votes = n() )

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'First'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

rr Combination %>% arrange( desc(votes) ) %>% head()

  1. Which Precinct had the highest number of ballots cast?
  • P-06 had the highest number of ballots cast.

rr Precinct <- Minneapolis2013 %>% group_by(Precinct) %>% summarise( votes = n() ) Precinct %>% arrange( desc(votes) ) %>% head()

Problem 7.5

  1. How has the result VoterData_A apparently been modified when compared to the original Minneapolis2013 data? What does a case represent in VoterData_A?
  • The result VoterData_A is same as the original Minneapolis2013 data.

rr VoterData_A <- Minneapolis2013 %>% group_by(First, Second) VoterData_A

  1. How has the result VoterData_B apparently been modified when compared to the original Minneapolis2013 data? What does a case represent in VoterData_B?
  • The result VoterData_B apparently been modified when compared to the original Minneapolis2013 data is the result VoterData_B only contains 1 row, which is the number of total cases of Minneapolis2013. The case represent in VoterData_B is the total row number of the whole data.

rr VoterData_B <- Minneapolis2013 %>% summarise( total = n() ) VoterData_B

  1. How has the result VoterData_C apparently been modified when compared to the original Minneapolis2013 data? What does a case represent in VoterData_C?
  • The result VoterData_C apparently been modified when compared to the original Minneapolis2013 is the VoterData_C table does not contain other columns, only contains three columns: First, Second, and total.The case represent in VoterData_C is the total votes in First and Second Vote selections.

rr VoterData_C <- Minneapolis2013 %>% group_by(First, Second) %>% summarise( total = n() )

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'First'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

rr VoterData_C

  1. Here, the group_by() and summarise() steps are reversed and now the result is an error indicating that “Column First is unknown.” Clearly the variable First existed in the Minneapolis2013 data frame, why is it now unknown?
  • This is because we use the summarise function first, and use group_by function next, the group_by() should always along with summarise().

rr VoterData_D <- Minneapolis2013 %>% summarise( total = n() ) %>% group_by(First, Second)

错误: Must group by variables found in `.data`.
* Column `First` is not found.
* Column `Second` is not found.
[90mRun `rlang::last_error()` to see where the error occurred.[39m

Problem 7.6

1.Make a scatter plot showing the relationship between land area and population for each state.

data("ZipGeography", package = "dcData")
head(ZipGeography)

ZipGeography[["Population"]][is.na(ZipGeography[["Population"]])] <- 0
ZipGeography[["LandArea"]][is.na(ZipGeography[["LandArea"]])] <- 0

ZipGeography_State <- 
  ZipGeography %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarise(Population = sum(Population), LandArea = sum(LandArea))

head(ZipGeography_State)

ggplot(ZipGeography_State) +
 aes(x = Population, y = LandArea, colour = State) +
 geom_point(size = 1L) +
 scale_color_hue() +
 theme_minimal()

  1. Make a choropleth map showing the population of each state.
ZipGeography %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarise(area = sum(LandArea,
                       na.rm = TRUE),
            population = sum(Population,
                             na.rm = TRUE))
ZipGeography %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarise(area = sum(LandArea,
                       na.rm = TRUE),
            population = sum(Population,
                             na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mUSMap(key = "State", fill = "population")
Mapping API still under development and may change in future releases.
2 items were not translated

  1. Make a choropleth map showing the population per unit area of each state.
ZipGeography %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarise(area = sum(LandArea, na.rm = TRUE),
            population = sum(Population,na.rm = TRUE),
            Density = (population / area),
            Density = pmin(Density, 500))
ZipGeography %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarise(area = sum(LandArea,na.rm = TRUE),
            population = sum(Population,na.rm = TRUE),
            Density = (population / area),
            Density = pmin(Density, 500))
  mUSMap(ZipGeography, key = "State", fill = "Density")
